      • ID_MOT_WHILE

        public static final int ID_MOT_WHILE
        Devices: 3D
        Mot_While [0, 1] 1 -> Motor polling -> Valid for the functions "a, pr, cf".
        If the flag is set, the answer to the command (e.g"pa: !“) is sent only if
        the motor (or both motors) has reached the position - In other cases the answer
        is sent if the motor (both motors) has been started - The value is not stored in
        flash and is 0 by default!
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • ID_BAT_S

        public static final int ID_BAT_S
        Devices: S910 - 3D
        Battery status (charge state).
        6 -> over the maximum value -> external voltage supply
        5 (full), 4 (3/4), 3 (1/2), 2 (1/4), 1 (almost empty)
        0 -> below lower voltage limit -> device is switched off without further information
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • ID_ISTATE

        public static final int ID_ISTATE
        Devices: S910 - 3D
        Level status [0..5].
        0 tilt plane "probably" up to date (depends on next value 1 or 3)
        1 Tilt plane was recently redetermined and is identical
        2 Tilt plane (old) cannot currently be measured (system overload)
        3 Tilt plane was recently redetermined (value has altered)
        4 Tilt plane has not yet been determined (after power up, level enabled)
        5 Tilt measurement deactivated
        6 Tilt plane "unstable" (possible reason vibrations, oscillations, …)
        Level status [0..5]
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • ID_EVLEV

        public static final java.lang.String ID_EVLEV
        Devices: 3D
        The tilt sensor generates events if the status has changed.
        The number outputted corresponds to the identifier "75" with the exception of the number "0"

        <event> EvLev: <number>
        <number>
        1 … The tilt plane was redetermined and is identical to the previous measurement
        2 … The tilt plane is "old" but can currently not be determined (system overload)
        3 … The tilt plane was redetermined but it has changed
        4 … The tilt plane could not yet be determined (after power up, level enabled)
        5 … The tilt plane is/was deactivated (level disabled)
        6 … The tilt measurement is unstable (measured value is changing continuously -> vibrations etc...)
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • ID_EVPOS

        public static final java.lang.String ID_EVPOS
        Devices: 3D
        This signals that a turning motor has stopped because it has either reached the intended position or for another reason (error situation) or has been prematurely stopped by the user "ps" (position top).
        An individual event is triggered for each motor. The commands "pa", "pr" and "cf" always generate events for both motors even if only one motor was supposed to have started (e.g - pa 22:4.7). The command "ps" also generates an event if the relevant motor or motors are stopped at this moment in time.
        If the commands "pa", "pr" or "cf" are interrupted with "ps", then only one event per motor is generated. This event indicates only that the moving motor has come to a stop, irrespective of whether it has reached the intended position or has been prematurely stopped by the "ps" command - "ps H" and "ps V" trigger the respective corresponding event, "ps B" generates events for both motors -
        If an error occurs with a motor, then an error message is output
        <event> EvPos: <letter> (<ok> | <error>)
        <letter> [V, H]
        V … Vertical motor, H … Horizontal motor
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

        public static final java.lang.String ID_EVKEY
        Devices: 3D
        Pressing a key on the remote control generates the "event" (Key down), when the key is released, another "Event" (Key up) is sent, the key code is transmitted along with both events.
        <event> EvKey: <number> <letter>
        <number> [0..31] Key code <letter> [d,u] d … "Key down", u … "Key up"

      • ID_EVBAT

        public static final java.lang.String ID_EVBAT
        Devices: 3D
        An event is generated when the external voltage supply is connected or disconnected. If the rechargeable battery voltage falls below a lower limit (battery almost empty), an event is likewise triggered, at any time after this occurs, the device can switch itself off (to protect the rechargeable batteries) without warning
        <event> EvLine: <String> <String>
        con - External voltage supply connected
        dis - External voltage supply disconnected/interrupted

        <event> EvBat: <String> <String> empty Battery is empty -> Device switches itself off soon after this
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • ID_EVMSG

        public static final java.lang.String ID_EVMSG
        Devices: 3D
        System messages (System Error (Fault) or Warning) System errors or warnings are indicated by the red LED.
        IDs 60 and 61 (16Bit variable) supply information about the causes, each variable can store 16 states, the setting or deletion of the individual Bits is signalled by this "event". The event supplies information if the state of one of the individual Bits changes.
        IDs 60 and 61 supply all the information about all the Bits (decimal number)

        <event> EvMsg: <letter1><letter2> <number>
        <letter1> [s, c] s.. set (Bit), c .. clear (Bit) <letter2> [F, W] F.. fault (system error), W .. warning
        <number> [0 .. 15] Bit (Flag)
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • ID_EVCAL

        public static final java.lang.String ID_EVCAL
        Devices: 3D
        This signals that the initiated self-calibration sequence has been ended. The feedback about success or failure is indicated by the parameters following the event name. If the calibration is successful, this is signalled by an "!".
        If it was a failure, the cause of the error is indicated in the error code "@EXXXX"

        <event> EvCal: (<ok> | <error>)
        See Also:
